      <div id="mainContent" class="main column clearfix"> 
       <h1>'Play the Long Game'</h1>
       <div class="alignRight newsimagelarge">
        <img src="/uploadedImages/_VMI/Communications_Marketing/Newscenter/Headlines/Headline_Images/13-14/ReaganConfMonAM2015krr_0220Fulltext.jpg" alt="FullTextImage/img/@alt" class="bordered">
        <span class="caption">Retired Navy Adm. James Stavridis addresses conference participants. – VMI Photo by Kevin Remington.</span>
       </div>
       <p class="sub-header-italic">Retired NATO Commander Talks About 21st-Century Challenges, Opportunities</p>
       <p>LEXINGTON, Va., Nov. 3, 2014 – The former NATO supreme allied commander Europe told an audience of VMI cadets, faculty, and Cold War scholars earlier today that building bridges, not walls, will be key to solving the myriad security challenges facing the global community in the 21st century.<br><br>Retired Navy Adm. James Stavridis, who served as NATO’s 16th commander from 2009 to 2013, gave the keynote address, “21st Century Security: Challenges and Opportunities,” as part of a Nov. 3-4 conference, “The Enduring Legacy: Leadership and National Security Affairs During the Ronald Reagan Era.” <br><br>The conference is sponsored by the John A. Adams ’71 Center for Military History and Strategic Analysis and the VMI Center for Leadership and Ethics. Approximately 230 scholars, including 27 panelists or speakers, have converged to attend the conference, the first of its kind offered by the Adams Center.</p>
       <div class="well">
        <blockquote class="pull-right">
         <p><strong>The Marshall Example: Outreach, Not Isolationism</strong></p>
         <p>For retired Navy Adm. James Stavridis, the old adage, “Those who cannot remember the past are condemned to repeat it,” is more than just a passing phrase; it’s a guiding principle.</p>
         <p>As part of “The Enduring Legacy: Leadership and National Security Affairs During the Ronald Reagan Era,” Stavridis spoke both before and during his keynote address about the danger of American isolationism.</p>
         <p>&nbsp;“There’s this enormous sense of fatigue, and particularly with the Middle East,” said Stavridis before his address. This is understandable, he acknowledged, after more than a decade of what he termed “unfulfilling” military action in Iraq and Afghanistan, and a price tag that soared past the $2 trillion mark.</p>
         <p>&nbsp;Despite this, Stavridis doesn’t have to look far to find an exemplar of a military man who strove past war fatigue to become a moral and military giant: General of the Army George C. Marshall, VMI class of 1901, whose post-World War II Marshall Plan helped Europe recover from the devastation of six years of war.</p>
         <p>&nbsp;The Marshall Plan is “probably the best single example of desire to engage in the world even when it doesn’t appear to be in your best interest in the short run to do so,” said Stavridis, who retired from a 37-year career with the Navy in 2013, after serving as NATO supreme allied commander Europe from 2009 to 2013. Stavridis was the first Navy officer to hold that position.</p>
         <p>&nbsp;Near the end of his remarks in Gillis Theater, Stavridis gave another reminder that the past should exist not in a dusty history book, or a seldom-visited Web page, but in the hearts and minds of engaged citizens today. Displaying an image of the program from the 1940 Army-Navy football game, Stavridis gestured to the back cover, which showed a warship plowing confidently forward. The caption, he noted, read “The unsinkable U.S.S. Arizona.”</p>
         <p>&nbsp;Just over a year later, the unsinkable ship was at the bottom of the Pacific Ocean, sunk by Japanese bombs during the Dec. 7, 1941, attack on Pearl Harbor. Said Stavridis, “The unexpected can and will overtake us.”</p>
         <p>&nbsp;That uncertainty, though, cannot be an excuse for avoiding engagement. As Stavridis noted before his address, “It would be a disaster if the American public [today] turned inward in a spate of isolationism.”</p>
         <small>Mary Price</small>
        </blockquote>&nbsp;
       </div>
       <p>In addition, approximately 320 cadets are involved in some way, said Lt. Col. Brad Coleman ’95, associate professor of history and director of the Adams Center. “I expect we’ll have about 40 percent of the Corps here at some point,” Coleman noted.<br><br><strong>National Security Challenges</strong><br>Speaking to a capacity crowd in Gillis Theater, Stavridis set the stage for discussing 21st-century security by offering a look at 20th-century security efforts that were tried – and failed.<br><br>In the first of several slides, Stavridis showed a group of cadets gathered for a class picture at the famed French military academy <em>École Spéciale Militaire de Saint-Cyr</em> in 1914, on the eve of the outbreak of World War I. By 1918, Stavridis said, everyone in the picture was dead.<br><br>“This is the beginning of 20th-century security, which is, let’s face it, a disaster,” said Stavridis, a 1976 graduate of the United States Naval Academy who is now dean of the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University.<br><br>Two decades later, he observed, it seemed as if the world had learned little from the conflict then called the Great War. A death toll of over 1 million in the World War II battle of Stalingrad alone was followed by what the retired Navy admiral called the “seemingly inevitable” collision between the United States and the Soviet Union.<br><br>The Berlin Wall, Stavridis said, became the pre-eminent image of 20th-century security.<br><br>For Stavridis, the realization that walls wouldn’t work anymore came on the calm and beautiful morning of Sept. 11, 2001, when he was just 200 feet and two floors away when an airplane hijacked by Islamic terrorists plowed into the Pentagon.<br><br>Then a newly minted one-star admiral, Stavridis was in his supervisor’s office when a glimpse of metal and a whooshing sound were followed by smoke and fire and flames.<br><br>“Here I was that day in the safest building in the world,” said Stavridis, “in the headquarters of the strongest military in the world, in the capital of the richest nation ever known. Was I safe on that day? … I think what we’re learning in the 21st century is that we have to find ways to build bridges, to play the long game, in order to create real security.”<br><br>Stavridis next led his audience through a quick but thorough overview of the world’s many “hot spots” of conflict—among them North Korea, Syria, the Ukraine, and Afghanistan – and commented on each. He also paid special attention to Asia, noting the “increasing assertiveness” of Japan and growing tensions in the Sino-Japanese relationship.<br><br>Stavridis also discussed issues straddling national or even regional borders, including the Ebola epidemic, cyber attacks, environmental concerns, economic inequality, political gridlock, and isolationism, before moving on to the second half of his talk: opportunities.<br><br><strong>Launching Ideas</strong><br>At this point, Stavridis told his audience, it’s time to roll up sleeves and get to work, rather than shrink back in anxiety or retreat into passivity. “So often the conversation stops with a long litany of fear and risk,” he observed. “We have to think, ‘What do we do about this?’”<br><br>Speaking to the numerous cadets in the audience, the admiral urged them to prepare for the 21st century’s challenges by listening, so as to better understand others, by learning languages, and by reading broadly from works of both fiction and non-fiction.<br><br>“To understand a time, read the literature of that time,” said Stavridis as he showed a montage of jackets from books he’d read while preparing for his role at NATO.<br><br>On a broader scale, Stavridis said he would like to see the international community pay more attention to issues such as cyber security – “We need a cyber force, and sooner than later,” he observed – the position of women across the globe, universal literacy and the increasingly important role of humanitarian missions such as the one the U.S. has recently launched in response to the Ebola epidemic.<br><br>Showing a photo of a U.S. Navy destroyer launching a Tomahawk missile, Stavridis observed, “[The Navy is] very, very good at launching Tomahawk missiles. We need to be better at launching ideas.”<br><br>Cooperation and bridge building, Stavridis believes, will take the United States and the global community places that wall-building never could.<br><br>“The challenges are immense if we look at them as a thicket out there,” said Stavridis in a question-and-answer period after his remarks. “But no one of us is as smart as all of us thinking together.”<br><br>Coleman, who met Stavridis while the two men were working together at the U.S. Southern Command in Miami seven years ago, said that plans for a conference on the Reagan era had been in the works long before he arrived at VMI as director of the Adams Center in 2012. The timing of this year’s conference, he noted, was quite fortuitous.<br><br>“The recent declassification of Reagan-administration records makes this the ideal moment for us to go back and look at the Reagan period … and think about the connections between the Reagan era and contemporary national security affairs,” said Coleman.<br><br><em>–Mary Price</em></p>
       <p align="center">&nbsp; -VMI-</p> 
